  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="Aink289-kilavi">iṟceṟitta piṉṉart tōḻi varaivukaṭāvuḻi mutirnta tiṉaippuṉam ivaḷ kāttoḻintāl 
          varaival eṉṟāṟk avaḷ colliyatu.
          </p>
        <p xml:lang="en"> 
          What she said to him who said, “If she leaves this well-ripened millet field unguarded, I will marry [her],” when the heroine’s confidante urged marriage after her confinement.
          </p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
      <lg xml:id="Aink289">
<l>koṭicci yiṉkural kiḷicet taṭukkattup</l>
<l>paiṅkura lēṉaṟ paṭartaruṅ kiḷiyeṉak</l>
<l>kāvaluṅ kaṭiyunar pōlvar</l>
<l>mālvarai nāṭa varaintaṉai koṇmō</l>
      </lg>
      <lg xml:lang="en">
        <l>O man from the land on the great mountain,</l>
        <l rend="space">saying that the parakeets</l>
        <l>that pervade the green-eared millet on the mountainside,</l>
        <l rend="space">hearing the pleasant voice</l>
        <l>of the creeper-like girl,</l>
        <l>think it to be that of a fellow parakeet,</l>
        <l rend="space">they seem to prevent her from guarding as well—</l>
        <l>so marry and take her.</l>
        
      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
